1.9.8	Your backup scheme is good , except that it should be your data drive , not your system drive that you are backing up ( unless you are storing your data on the system drive ) .	St
1.9.9	But now lets consider this scenario : It is the morning of Friday April 14 , 2006 , and the scheduled backup has not yet occurred .	St
1.9.10	Like a million or so Americans , you have spent the past several days gathering your financial data for the year and putting it into spreadsheets to consolidate it and calculate the totals and subtotals , etc .	St
1.9.11	etc. , needed for Federal and State income tax forms .	St
1.9.12	Suddenly , your disk crashes badly so that there is no way to recover the data in a hurry .	St
1.9.13	Your last backup was last Friday , so none of your work for the week is on it you must start all over , and the deadline is tomorrow .	St
1.9.14	Had you had RAID 1 ( mirroring ) it is unlikely that both of the drives would have failed , so all your data would be intact on the good drive ; you could recover it and proceed in filing your 1040 and state forms .	St
1.9.15	This is , I think , is the proper role for RAID 1 to provide automatic redundancy for important data generated between regularly scheduled backups .	St
1.9.16	With RAID 5 , I might rely more heavily on it and reduce the frequency of scheduled backups -- but not eliminate them .	St
1.9.17	These are , of course , my ideas and how I tend to operate ; I know that not everyone agrees with me .	St
